(54, 1, '2013-11-10 20:56:29', '2013-11-10 20:56:29', '<i>Äsana</i> (à¤à¤¸à¤¨) is yoga posture. It''s such a posture, where the whole body works together. There is harmony and union in-between all the parts of the body as well as all the layers (koshas). The mind is ever-present but still and one-pointed.\r\n\r\nStiffness and dullness is replaced by poise and serenity.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" width="883" height="512" /></p>\r\nà¤¸à¥à¤¥à¤¿à¤°à¤¸à¥à¤à¤®à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨à¤®à¥à¥¥à¥ªà¥¬à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.46 : Sthira Suhka Äsanam</b>\r\n\r\n<i>yoga postures implies steadiness and ease</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢sthira = steady, stable, motionless</li>\r\n	<li>â¢sukham = comfortable, ease filled</li>\r\n	<li>â¢asanam = meditation posture</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nà¤ªà¥à¤°à¤¯à¤¤à¥à¤¨à¤¶à¥à¤¥à¤¿à¤²à¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤¨à¤¨à¥à¤¤à¥à¤¯à¤¸à¤®à¤¾à¤ªà¤¤à¥à¤¤à¤¿à¤­à¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤®à¥à¥¥à¥ªà¥­à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.47: Prayatna Åaithilya Ananta SamÄpattibhyÄmÂ </b>\r\n\r\n<i>this only happens once the effort to maintain the posture lessens and one surrenders to the infinite one Â </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢prayatna = effort, endeavor</li>\r\n	<li>â¢shaithilya = by relaxing, loosening, lessening, slackening</li>\r\n	<li>â¢ananta = infinite, endlessness</li>\r\n	<li>â¢samapattibhyam = by focusing attention on, by coalescence, coincidence, merging</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nà¤¤à¤¤à¥ à¤¦à¥à¤µà¤¨à¥à¤¦à¥à¤µà¤¾à¤¨à¤­à¤¿à¤à¤¾à¤¤à¤à¥¥à¥ªà¥®à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.48: Tatah DvandvÄh AnabhighÄtahÂ </b>\r\n\r\n<i>then one becomes impartial to the opposing sensations like pleasure and pain, heat and cold, honour and dishonour</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢tatah = then, thereby, from that</li>\r\n	<li>â¢dvandva = opposites, dualities</li>\r\n	<li>â¢anabhighata = cessation of disturbance</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWhen the mind is still, the Self can be felt.\r\n\r\nBy understanding the true meaning of yog; union, the path is clear and the obstacles become visible. By using our bodies and the various Asanas with understanding, we are able to remove these obstacles, and start pursuing the yogic path. Due to the modern lifestyle, we are often completely removed from nature. Our bodies are imbalanced, and the natural intelligence of the body is well hidden behind the stiffness and unconsciousness. It takes a long time to reverse the process and reestablish the lost balance. One should be aware of this obstacle and not to confuse the achievement of Asana for a goal of Yoga. Once the balance is restored, Asana becomes a gate for deep exploration of the Breath and Life force (Prana), Senses(Indria), Mind(Manas), Individual Soul (Atman) and the Universal Soul (Brahman, Ananda) . The next stages of Ashtanga yoga guide us through.\r\n\r\nFrom this point the achievement of Asana is just the beginning of the pursuit, rather than the end.', 'Äsana', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'asana', '', '', '2013-12-02 16:45:16', '2013-12-02 16:45:16', '', 41, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?page_id=54', 3, 'page', '', 0),
