(56, 1, '2013-11-10 20:58:33', '2013-11-10 20:58:33', '<i>PrÄnÄyÄma</i> (à¤ªà¥à¤°à¤¾à¤£à¤¾à¤¯à¤¾à¤®), is the practice of the control of the flow of energy in the body. It is done using techniques of extension and retention of the breathe. The life force (prana) is freed to flow through out the body and vitality, health and stability are invited with this practice.\r\n\r\nSteady practice of Asanas is inevitable base for Pranayama practice.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" width="883" height="512" /></p>\r\nà¤¤à¤¸à¥à¤®à¤¿à¤¨à¥ à¤¸à¤¤à¤¿ à¤¶à¥à¤µà¤¾à¤¸à¤ªà¥à¤°à¤¶à¥à¤µà¤¾à¤¸à¤¯à¥à¤°à¥à¤à¤¤à¤¿à¤µà¤¿à¤à¥à¤à¥à¤¦à¤ à¤ªà¥à¤°à¤¾à¤£à¤¾à¤¯à¤¾à¤®à¤à¥¥à¥ªà¥¯à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.49: Tasmin SatiÅvÄsa PraÅvÄsayoh Gativicchedah PrÄnÄyÄmahÂ </b>\r\n\r\n<i>the next step is Pranayama, regulation of inhalation and exhalation with retention</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢tasmin = upon that (perfection of Asana)</li>\r\n	<li>â¢sati = being accomplished</li>\r\n	<li>â¢shvasa = inhalation</li>\r\n	<li>â¢prashvsayoh = exhalation</li>\r\n	<li>â¢gati = movements</li>\r\n	<li>â¢vichchhedah = cessation, interruption</li>\r\n	<li>â¢pranayamah = expansion of prana (life force) through regulation of breath</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nà¤¬à¤¾à¤¹à¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤­à¥à¤¯à¤¨à¥à¤¤à¤°à¤¸à¥à¤¤à¤®à¥à¤­à¤µà¥à¤¤à¥à¤¤à¤¿à¤°à¥à¤¦à¥à¤¶à¤à¤¾à¤²à¤¸à¤à¤à¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤­à¤¿à¤ à¤ªà¤°à¤¿à¤¦à¥à¤·à¥à¤à¥ à¤¦à¥à¤°à¥à¤à¤¸à¥à¤à¥à¤·à¥à¤®à¤à¥¥à¥«à¥¦à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.50: BÄhya abhyantara stambha vrittiá¸¥ deÅa kÄla sankhyÄbhih paridriá¹£á¹­aá¸¥ dÄ«rgha sÅ«ká¹£maá¸¥</b>\r\n\r\n<i>the three movements; prolonged and subtle exhalation, inhalation and retention of breath, are regulated by positioning, timing and number of cycles of breathÂ </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢bahya = external</li>\r\n	<li>â¢abhyantara = internal</li>\r\n	<li>