(60, 1, '2013-11-10 21:02:12', '2013-11-10 21:02:12', '<i>PratyÄhÄra</i> (à¤ªà¥à¤°à¤¤à¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤¹à¤¾à¤°) is withdrawal of the senses. The presence of this state of mind is inevitable for further persuasion inside.\r\n\r\nThe senses are our gateways to the outer world. They constantly receive input from nature and convey it to the mind. The mind is drawn automatically towards these experiences and tends to fluctuate from one thing to another.\r\n\r\nWith the body freed by Asanas and the mind stilled by Pranayama, the senses are more easily withdrawn in to PratyÄhÄra.\r\n\r\nThen the ever-active surroundings do not automatically transform into fluctuations of the mind and one is able to explore the inner world.\r\n\r\nThis stillness allows us to follow up the strong attraction inwards to explore the Source of all existence.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" width="883" height="512" /></p>\r\nà¤¸à¥à¤µà¤µà¤¿à¤·à¤¯à¤¾à¤¸à¤à¤ªà¥à¤°à¤¯à¥à¤à¥ à¤à¤¿à¤¤à¥à¤¤à¤¸à¥à¤¯ à¤¸à¥à¤µà¤°à¥à¤ªà¤¾à¤¨à¥à¤à¤¾à¤° à¤à¤µà¥à¤¨à¥à¤¦à¥à¤°à¤¿à¤¯à¤¾à¤£à¤¾à¤ à¤ªà¥à¤°à¤¤à¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤¹à¤¾à¤°à¤à¥¥à¥«à¥ªà¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.54: Sva viÅaya asamprayoge cittasya svarupe anukÄraá¸¥ iva indriyÄá¹am pratyÄhÄraá¸¥Â </b>\r\n\r\n<i>prayahara is the restoration of senses to the original purity of mind, by renouncing external objects</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢sva = their own</li>\r\n	<li>â¢vishaya = objects, region, spheres, realms, fields</li>\r\n	<li>â¢asamprayoge = not coming into contact with, cessation of engagement</li>\r\n	<li>â¢chittasya = of the mind field</li>\r\n	<li>â¢svarupe = own form, own nature (sva = own; rupe = form, nature)</li>\r\n	<li>â¢anukarah = imitate, resemble, follow, be engaged with</li>\r\n	<li>â¢iva = like, as though, as it were</li>\r\n	<li>â¢indriyanam = mental organs of actions and senses</li>\r\n	<li>â¢pratyaharah = withdrawal of the indriyas (the senses), bringing inward</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nà¤¤à¤¤à¤ à¤ªà¤°à¤®à¤¾ à¤µà¤¶à¥à¤¯à¤¤à¥à¤¨à¥à¤¦à¥à¤°à¤¿à¤¯à¤¾à¤£à¤¾à¤®à¥à¥¥à¥«à¥«à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.55: Tatah parama vaÅyata indriyaá¹amÂ </b>\r\n\r\n<i>this leads to the absolute control of the sense organs</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢tatah = then, thereby, from that</li>\r\n	<li>â¢parama = highest, supreme, ultimate, perfected</li>\r\n	<li>â¢vashyata = mastery, control, being willed</li>\r\n	<li>â¢indriyanam = of the mental organs of actions and senses</li>\r\n</ul>', 'PratyÄhÄra', '', 'publish', 'open', 'closed', '', 'pratyahara', '', '', '2013-12-02 16:46:04', '2013-12-02 16:46:04', '', 41, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/?page_id=60', 5, 'page', '', 0),
