(193, 1, '2013-12-02 16:45:02', '2013-12-02 16:45:02', '<i>Niyama</i> (à¤¨à¤¿à¤¯à¤®) means moral discipline for the individual. It forms the second rung of Aá¹£á¹­Änga yoga. <i>Niyama</i> relates to us at the individual level as opposed to <i>Yama </i>that is at a social level.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" width="883" height="512" /></p>\r\nThe five <i>Niyama </i>are:\r\n\r\n<i>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  </i><b><i>Saucha :</i></b><i> Cleanliness</i>\r\n\r\nà¤¶à¥à¤à¤¾à¤¤à¥ à¤¸à¥à¤µà¤¾à¤à¥à¤à¤à¥à¤à¥à¤ªà¥à¤¸à¤¾ à¤ªà¤°à¥à¤°à¤¸à¤à¤¸à¤°à¥à¤à¤à¥¥à¥ªà¥¦à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.40: Sauchat sva-anga jugupsa paraiá¸¥ asaá¹sargaá¸¥Â </b>\r\n\r\n<i>through cleanliness and purity of body and mind one will become impartial towards one''s own body and bodies of othersÂ </i>\r\n\r\nà¤¸à¤¤à¥à¤¤à¥à¤µà¤¶à¥à¤¦à¥à¤§à¤¿à¤¸à¥à¤®à¤¨à¤¸à¥à¤¯à¥à¤à¤¾à¤à¥à¤°à¥à¤¯à¥à¤¨à¥à¤¦à¥à¤°à¤¿à¤¯à¤à¤¯à¤¾à¤¤à¥à¤®à¤¦à¤°à¥à¤¶à¤¨à¤¯à¥à¤à¥à¤¯à¤¤à¥à¤µà¤¾à¤¨à¤¿<i> à¤à¥¥à¥ªà¥§à¥¥</i>\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.41: Sattva Åuddhi saumanasya ekÄgra indriya-jaya Ätma darÅana yogyatvÄni chaÂ </b>\r\n\r\n<i>with the body and mind cleansed, the senses will be under control, the mind will be content and prepared to experience the inward endeavor</i>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<i>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  </i><b><i>SantoÅa :</i></b><i> Contentment</i>\r\n\r\nà¤¸à¤à¤¤à¥à¤·à¤¾à¤¦à¤¨à¥à¤¤à¥à¤¤à¤®à¤¸à¥à¤à¤²à¤¾à¤­à¤à¥¥à¥ªà¥¨à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.42: Santoá¹£a anuttamah sukha lÄbhah</b>\r\n\r\n<i>contentment brings supreme happiness</i>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<i>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  </i><b><i>Tapas :</i></b><i> Penance</i>\r\n\r\nà¤à¤¾à¤¯à¥à¤¨à¥à¤¦à¥à¤°à¤¿à¤¯à¤¸à¤¿à¤¦à¥à¤§à¤¿à¤°à¤¶à¥à¤¦à¥à¤§à¤¿à¤à¥à¤·à¤¯à¤¾à¤¤à¥à¤¤à¤ªà¤¸à¤à¥¥à¥ªà¥©à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.43: KÄyÄ Indriya siddhiá¸¥ aÅuddhi kÅayÄt tapasah</b>\r\n\r\n<i>austerity destroys impurity and brings mastery over the body, senses and mind</i>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<i>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  </i><b><i>SvÄdhyÄya :</i></b><i> Self-study</i>\r\n\r\nà¤¸à¥à¤µà¤¾à¤§à¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤¯à¤¾à¤¦à¤¿à¤·à¥à¤à¤¦à¥à¤µà¤¤à¤¾à¤¸à¤à¤ªà¥à¤°à¤¯à¥à¤à¤à¥¥à¥ªà¥ªà¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.44:Â  SvÄdhyÄyÄt ishta samprayogah</b>\r\n\r\n<i>from self-study and reflection on sacred words, one attains contact and communionÂ  with that underlying natural realityÂ </i>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<i>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  </i><b><i>ÄªÅvara Praá¹idhÄna :</i></b><i> Faith</i>\r\n\r\nà¤¸à¤®à¤¾à¤§à¤¿à¤¸à¤¿à¤¦à¥à¤§à¤¿à¤°à¥à¤¶à¥à¤µà¤°à¤ªà¥à¤°à¤£à¤¿à¤§à¤¾à¤¨à¤¾à¤¤à¥à¥¥à¥ªà¥«à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.45: SamÄdhi siddhiá¸¥ Ä«shvarapranidhÄna</b>\r\n\r\n<i>from an attitude of letting go into one''s source, the illuminate state of perfect concentration called Samadhi is attained</i>', 'Niyama', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '52-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-12-02 16:45:02', '2013-12-02 16:45:02', '', 52, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/posts/52-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(194, 1, '2013-12-02 16:45:16', '2013-12-02 16:45:16', '<i>Äsana</i> (à¤à¤¸à¤¨) is yoga posture. It''s such a posture, where the whole body works together. There is harmony and union in-between all the parts of the body as well as all the layers (koshas). The mind is ever-present but still and one-pointed.\r\n\r\nStiffness and dullness is replaced by poise and serenity.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" width="883" height="512" /></p>\r\nà¤¸à¥à¤¥à¤¿à¤°à¤¸à¥à¤à¤®à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨à¤®à¥à¥¥à¥ªà¥¬à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.46 : Sthira Suhka Äsanam</b>\r\n\r\n<i>yoga postures implies steadiness and ease</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢sthira = steady, stable, motionless</li>\r\n	<li>â¢sukham = comfortable, ease filled</li>\r\n	<li>â¢asanam = meditation posture</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nà¤ªà¥à¤°à¤¯à¤¤à¥à¤¨à¤¶à¥à¤¥à¤¿à¤²à¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤¨à¤¨à¥à¤¤à¥à¤¯à¤¸à¤®à¤¾à¤ªà¤¤à¥à¤¤à¤¿à¤­à¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤®à¥à¥¥à¥ªà¥­à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.47: Prayatna Åaithilya Ananta SamÄpattibhyÄmÂ </b>\r\n\r\n<i>this only happens once the effort to maintain the posture lessens and one surrenders to the infinite one Â </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢prayatna = effort, endeavor</li>\r\n	<li>â¢shaithilya = by relaxing, loosening, lessening, slackening</li>\r\n	<li>â¢ananta = infinite, endlessness</li>\r\n	<li>â¢samapattibhyam = by focusing attention on, by coalescence, coincidence, merging</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nà¤¤à¤¤à¥ à¤¦à¥à¤µà¤¨à¥à¤¦à¥à¤µà¤¾à¤¨à¤­à¤¿à¤à¤¾à¤¤à¤à¥¥à¥ªà¥®à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.48: Tatah DvandvÄh AnabhighÄtahÂ </b>\r\n\r\n<i>then one becomes impartial to the opposing sensations like pleasure and pain, heat and cold, honour and dishonour</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢tatah = then, thereby, from that</li>\r\n	<li>â¢dvandva = opposites, dualities</li>\r\n	<li>â¢anabhighata = cessation of disturbance</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWhen the mind is still, the Self can be felt.\r\n\r\nBy understanding the true meaning of yog; union, the path is clear and the obstacles become visible. By using our bodies and the various Asanas with understanding, we are able to remove these obstacles, and start pursuing the yogic path. Due to the modern lifestyle, we are often completely removed from nature. Our bodies are imbalanced, and the natural intelligence of the body is well hidden behind the stiffness and unconsciousness. It takes a long time to reverse the process and reestablish the lost balance. One should be aware of this obstacle and not to confuse the achievement of Asana for a goal of Yoga. Once the balance is restored, Asana becomes a gate for deep exploration of the Breath and Life force (Prana), Senses(Indria), Mind(Manas), Individual Soul (Atman) and the Universal Soul (Brahman, Ananda) . The next stages of Ashtanga yoga guide us through.\r\n\r\nFrom this point the achievement of Asana is just the beginning of the pursuit, rather than the end.', 'Äsana', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '54-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-12-02 16:45:16', '2013-12-02 16:45:16', '', 54, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/posts/54-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(195, 1, '2013-12-02 16:45:49', '2013-12-02 16:45:49', '<i>PrÄnÄyÄma</i> (à¤ªà¥à¤°à¤¾à¤£à¤¾à¤¯à¤¾à¤®), is the practice of the control of the flow of energy in the body. It is done using techniques of extension and retention of the breathe. The life force (prana) is freed to flow through out the body and vitality, health and stability are invited with this practice.\r\n\r\nSteady practice of Asanas is inevitable base for Pranayama practice.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" width="883" height="512" /></p>\r\nà¤¤à¤¸à¥à¤®à¤¿à¤¨à¥ à¤¸à¤¤à¤¿ à¤¶à¥à¤µà¤¾à¤¸à¤ªà¥à¤°à¤¶à¥à¤µà¤¾à¤¸à¤¯à¥à¤°à¥à¤à¤¤à¤¿à¤µà¤¿à¤à¥à¤à¥à¤¦à¤ à¤ªà¥à¤°à¤¾à¤£à¤¾à¤¯à¤¾à¤®à¤à¥¥à¥ªà¥¯à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.49: Tasmin SatiÅvÄsa PraÅvÄsayoh Gativicchedah PrÄnÄyÄmahÂ </b>\r\n\r\n<i>the next step is Pranayama, regulation of inhalation and exhalation with retention</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢tasmin = upon that (perfection of Asana)</li>\r\n	<li>â¢sati = being accomplished</li>\r\n	<li>â¢shvasa = inhalation</li>\r\n	<li>â¢prashvsayoh = exhalation</li>\r\n	<li>â¢gati = movements</li>\r\n	<li>â¢vichchhedah = cessation, interruption</li>\r\n	<li>â¢pranayamah = expansion of prana (life force) through regulation of breath</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nà¤¬à¤¾à¤¹à¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤­à¥à¤¯à¤¨à¥à¤¤à¤°à¤¸à¥à¤¤à¤®à¥à¤­à¤µà¥à¤¤à¥à¤¤à¤¿à¤°à¥à¤¦à¥à¤¶à¤à¤¾à¤²à¤¸à¤à¤à¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤­à¤¿à¤ à¤ªà¤°à¤¿à¤¦à¥à¤·à¥à¤à¥ à¤¦à¥à¤°à¥à¤à¤¸à¥à¤à¥à¤·à¥à¤®à¤à¥¥à¥«à¥¦à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.50: BÄhya abhyantara stambha vrittiá¸¥ deÅa kÄla sankhyÄbhih paridriá¹£á¹­aá¸¥ dÄ«rgha sÅ«ká¹£maá¸¥</b>\r\n\r\n<i>the three movements; prolonged and subtle exhalation, inhalation and retention of breath, are regulated by positioning, timing and number of cycles of breathÂ </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢bahya = external</li>\r\n	<li>â¢abhyantara = internal</li>\r\n	<li>â¢stambha = holding, restraint, suspension, retention, cessation</li>\r\n	<li>â¢vrittih = movements, fluctuations</li>\r\n	<li>â¢desha = place, spot, space, location</li>\r\n	<li>â¢kala = time, period, duration</li>\r\n	<li>â¢sankhyabhih = by these three, number, count of</li>\r\n	<li>â¢paridrishtah = regulated by, observed by</li>\r\n	<li>â¢dirgha = made long, prolonged, slow</li>\r\n	<li>â¢sukshmah = and subtle, fine</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nà¤¬à¤¾à¤¹à¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤­à¥à¤¯à¤¨à¥à¤¤à¤°à¤µà¤¿à¤·à¤¯à¤¾à¤à¥à¤·à¥à¤ªà¥ à¤à¤¤à¥à¤°à¥à¤¥à¤à¥¥à¥«à¥§à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.51: BÄhya abhyantara viÅaya aká¹£epi chaturthaá¸¥Â </b>\r\n\r\n<i>beyond this is the froth method of breathing, which surpasses the internal and external realms of breathÂ </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢bahya = external</li>\r\n	<li>â¢abhyantara = internal</li>\r\n	<li>â¢vishaya = region, spheres, realms, fields</li>\r\n	<li>â¢akshepi = going beyond, surpassing, setting aside</li>\r\n	<li>â¢chaturthah = the fourth</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nà¤¤à¤¤à¤ à¤à¥à¤·à¥à¤¯à¤¤à¥ à¤ªà¥à¤°à¤à¤¾à¤¶à¤¾à¤µà¤°à¤£à¤®à¥à¥¥à¥«à¥¨à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.52: Tataá¸¥ kÅÄ«yate prakaÅa ÄvaranamÂ </b>\r\n\r\n<i>than the veil covering the illumination vanishesÂ </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢tatah = then, thereby, thence, from that</li>\r\n	<li>â¢kshiyate = is destroyed, thinned, diminishes, vanishes</li>\r\n	<li>â¢prakasha = light, illumination</li>\r\n	<li>â¢avaranam = veil, covering<i>\r\n</i></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nPranayama is the highest discipline on the yogic path. The most powerful tool of <b><i>practice</i></b> (Abhyasa) to allow the next four stages to happen through letting go or <b><i>renunciation</i></b> (Vairagya).\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe initiation of this practice is done by experienced teacher to avoid damage to the nervous system which can be caused by incorrect and inappropriate use of the techniques.', 'PrÄnÄyÄma', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '56-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-12-02 16:45:49', '2013-12-02 16:45:49', '', 56, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/posts/56-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(196, 1, '2013-12-02 16:46:04', '2013-12-02 16:46:04', '<i>PratyÄhÄra</i> (à¤ªà¥à¤°à¤¤à¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤¹à¤¾à¤°) is withdrawal of the senses. The presence of this state of mind is inevitable for further persuasion inside.\r\n\r\nThe senses are our gateways to the outer world. They constantly receive input from nature and convey it to the mind. The mind is drawn automatically towards these experiences and tends to fluctuate from one thing to another.\r\n\r\nWith the body freed by Asanas and the mind stilled by Pranayama, the senses are more easily withdrawn in to PratyÄhÄra.\r\n\r\nThen the ever-active surroundings do not automatically transform into fluctuations of the mind and one is able to explore the inner world.\r\n\r\nThis stillness allows us to follow up the strong attraction inwards to explore the Source of all existence.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" width="883" height="512" /></p>\r\nà¤¸à¥à¤µà¤µà¤¿à¤·à¤¯à¤¾à¤¸à¤à¤ªà¥à¤°à¤¯à¥à¤à¥ à¤à¤¿à¤¤à¥à¤¤à¤¸à¥à¤¯ à¤¸à¥à¤µà¤°à¥à¤ªà¤¾à¤¨à¥à¤à¤¾à¤° à¤à¤µà¥à¤¨à¥à¤¦à¥à¤°à¤¿à¤¯à¤¾à¤£à¤¾à¤ à¤ªà¥à¤°à¤¤à¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤¹à¤¾à¤°à¤à¥¥à¥«à¥ªà¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.54: Sva viÅaya asamprayoge cittasya svarupe anukÄraá¸¥ iva indriyÄá¹am pratyÄhÄraá¸¥Â </b>\r\n\r\n<i>prayahara is the restoration of senses to the original purity of mind, by renouncing external objects</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢sva = their own</li>\r\n	<li>â¢vishaya = objects, region, spheres, realms, fields</li>\r\n	<li>â¢asamprayoge = not coming into contact with, cessation of engagement</li>\r\n	<li>â¢chittasya = of the mind field</li>\r\n	<li>â¢svarupe = own form, own nature (sva = own; rupe = form, nature)</li>\r\n	<li>â¢anukarah = imitate, resemble, follow, be engaged with</li>\r\n	<li>â¢iva = like, as though, as it were</li>\r\n	<li>â¢indriyanam = mental organs of actions and senses</li>\r\n	<li>â¢pratyaharah = withdrawal of the indriyas (the senses), bringing inward</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nà¤¤à¤¤à¤ à¤ªà¤°à¤®à¤¾ à¤µà¤¶à¥à¤¯à¤¤à¥à¤¨à¥à¤¦à¥à¤°à¤¿à¤¯à¤¾à¤£à¤¾à¤®à¥à¥¥à¥«à¥«à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.55: Tatah parama vaÅyata indriyaá¹amÂ </b>\r\n\r\n<i>this leads to the absolute control of the sense organs</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢tatah = then, thereby, from that</li>\r\n	<li>â¢parama = highest, supreme, ultimate, perfected</li>\r\n	<li>â¢vashyata = mastery, control, being willed</li>\r\n	<li>â¢indriyanam = of the mental organs of actions and senses</li>\r\n</ul>', 'PratyÄhÄra', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '60-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-12-02 16:46:04', '2013-12-02 16:46:04', '', 60, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/posts/60-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(197, 1, '2013-12-02 16:46:17', '2013-12-02 16:46:17', '<i>DhÄranÄ</i> (à¤§à¤¾à¤°à¤£à¤¾) is another involutionary stage of yoga. Literally it means concentration. In this state the mind is intensely focussed in one-pointed concentration.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" width="883" height="512" /></p>\r\nà¤§à¤¾à¤°à¤£à¤¾à¤¸à¥ à¤ à¤¯à¥à¤à¥à¤¯à¤¤à¤¾ à¤®à¤¨à¤¸à¤à¥¥à¥«à¥©à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 2.53: DhÄranÄsu Äa YogyatÄ ManasahÂ </b>\r\n\r\n<i>the fourth Pranayama prepares the mind for concentration</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢dharanasu = for concentration, for dharana</li>\r\n	<li>â¢cha = and</li>\r\n	<li>â¢yogyata = fitness, preparedness, qualification, capability</li>\r\n	<li>â¢manasah = mind</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nà¤¦à¥à¤¶à¤¬à¤¨à¥à¤§à¤¶à¥à¤à¤¿à¤¤à¥à¤¤à¤¸à¥à¤¯ à¤§à¤¾à¤°à¤£à¤¾à¥¥à¥§à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 3.1: DeÅah bandhah cittasya dhÄranÄÂ </b>\r\n\r\n<i>attention fixed upon one point is DhÄranÄ; concentration Â </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢deshah = place, object, point, spot</li>\r\n	<li>â¢bandhah = binding to, holding, fixing, uniting</li>\r\n	<li>â¢chittasya = of the mind, consciousness</li>\r\n	<li>â¢dharana = concentration, focusing, directing attention</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;', 'DhÄranÄ', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '58-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-12-02 16:46:17', '2013-12-02 16:46:17', '', 58, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/posts/58-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(198, 1, '2013-12-02 16:46:30', '2013-12-02 16:46:30', '<i>DhyÄna</i> (à¤§à¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤¨) or meditation is a blissful state of mind where one''s consciousness is absorbed in the essence of the object of contemplation. This state is a result of dedicated practice of the previous (especially involutionary) stages.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" width="883" height="512" /></p>\r\nà¤¤à¤¤à¥à¤° à¤ªà¥à¤°à¤¤à¥à¤¯à¤¯à¥à¤à¤¤à¤¾à¤¨à¤¤à¤¾ à¤§à¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤¨à¤®à¥à¥¥à¥¨à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 3.2: Tatra Pratyaya EkatÄnatÄ DhyÄnamÂ Â </b>\r\n\r\n<i>the union of mind and the object is Dyana; meditation</i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢tatra = there, therein (in that place or desha of 3.1)</li>\r\n	<li>â¢pratyaya = the cause, the feeling, causal or cognitive principle, notion, content of mind, presented idea, cognition</li>\r\n	<li>â¢ekatanata = one continuous flow of uninterrupted attention (eka = one; tanata = continued directedness)</li>\r\n	<li>â¢dhyanam = meditation</li>\r\n</ul>', 'DhyÄna', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '62-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-12-02 16:46:30', '2013-12-02 16:46:30', '', 62, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/posts/62-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(199, 1, '2013-12-02 16:46:58', '2013-12-02 16:46:58', '<i>SamÄdhi</i> (à¤¸à¤®à¤¾à¤§à¤¿) is the final stage of the path of Yoga. It may be roughly translated as liberation. Through constant practice of meditation, the mind unites with the source of creation.\r\n\r\nThe individual soul (<i>Ätman</i>) fuses with the cosmic consciousness (<i>brahman</i>)\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="aligncenter  wp-image-43" alt="Ashtanga Yoga" src="http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/shapeimage_42.png" width="883" height="512" /></p>\r\nà¤¤à¤¦à¥à¤µà¤¾à¤°à¥à¤¥à¤®à¤¾à¤¤à¥à¤°à¤¨à¤¿à¤°à¥à¤­à¤¾à¤¸à¤ à¤¸à¥à¤µà¤°à¥à¤ªà¤¶à¥à¤¨à¥à¤¯à¤®à¤¿à¤µ à¤¸à¤®à¤¾à¤§à¤¿à¤à¥¥à¥©à¥¥\r\n\r\n<b>PYS 3.3: Tadeva ArthamÄtranirbhÄsam SvarÅ«paÅÅ«nyam Iva SamÄdhih Â </b>\r\n\r\n<i>when only the essence of the object shines forth in the mind, as if devoid of it''s own form,Â </i>\r\n\r\n<i>that state of deep absorption is Samadhi.Â </i>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>â¢tad = that</li>\r\n	<li>â¢eva = the same</li>\r\n	<li>â¢artha = object, place, point</li>\r\n	<li>â¢matra = only, alone</li>\r\n	<li>â¢nirbhasam = shines forth, appears</li>\r\n	<li>â¢svarupa = own form, own nature (sva = own; rupe = form, nature)</li>\r\n	<li>â¢shunyam = devoid of, empty</li>\r\n	<li>â¢iva = as if, as it were</li>\r\n	<li>â¢samadhih = meditation in its higher state, deep absorption of meditation, the state of perfected concentration, spiritual absorption</li>\r\n</ul>', 'SamÄdhi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '64-revision-v1', '', '', '2013-12-02 16:46:58', '2013-12-02 16:46:58', '', 64, 'http://localhost:8888/wpyogdiksha-nov2013/posts/64-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
